IMO people should be allowed to say whatever they want within the bounds
of safety. (Shouting fire in the cinema is out)

That leads us to a discussion of whether other people are compelled to
repeat their words, or to facilitate their words reaching a large
audience.

I believe the right to decline a broadcast, or to edit a recording
before broadcast is a valid extension of the right to free speech.

Just because someone says something does not mean another person is
compelled to broadcast it.

The award recipient had the right to say what she did. The Catholic
president had the right to lobby to have the speech edited before
broadcast. The broadcaster had the right to edit the recording and
broadcast the edited version. A chain of preservation of individual
rights.

