X may well have the right to speak or write freely.
Y may have the right to listen or read what X writes.
But W does not have an obligation to convey what X says to Y.
W can do so if s/he chooses however.
This is freedom of speech.

If an obligation is imposed on W to convey what X says to Y, W no longer
has freedom of speech.

Freedom of speech implies a freedom not to speak. If someone, or some
organisation, is forced to say something against their will, they no
longer have freedom of speech.

Freedom of speech does not mean others must listen to what you say
either. Some people think that others must listen to whatever they have
to say for freedom of speech to exist. This simply isn't true.

Those who think others should be forced to listen to what they have to
say, or be forced to repeat what they have to say, miss the whole point
of freedom.

Free people are free to ignore others as well as listen to their views.

Forcing someone to listen, or to repeat your words when they do not
voluntarily choose to do so is the antithesis of freedom.

