When I talk about rights, such as the right to free speech, I like to
point out that a right cannot exist alone. For every right there is a
complementary obligation. Take free speech for example. For free speech
to exist, society must observe the complementary obligation to let
others speak freely.

This does not mean that every time someone opens his or her mouth we
must politely pay attention until they have finished. It simply means we
should not stop them from speaking. We are free to ignore what they say.

Every society places limitations on the right to free speech. If someone
starts making a political speech in the middle of a theatre performance
they are quite rightly ejected from the venue. If people &quot;heckle&quot;
another speaker that people have gathered to hear, the same applies. If
someone starts making anti-Christian remarks in an inappropriate forum,
they may find their words edited from a broadcast.

Freedom of speech does not mean you have the right to access a mass
communication channel owned or controlled by someone else.

What it does mean is that you have the right to express your opinion
using the means at your disposal.

A soap box in a public park may be the only means at your disposal. If
so, you will have to learn to live with that situation.

Certainly it may irk you that others have more effective means of
communication at their disposal. But this is akin to the envy a
pedestrian feels as someone sweeps by in a Mercedes saloon car on a
rainy day. It really has nothing to do with freedom at all.

